[1]
Date: Thu 12 Jun 2003
From: "David M. White" <DMWhite@uwyo.edu>

A comment on transportation of suspected monkeypox-infected animals
--------------------------------------------------
Aren't the orthopoxviruses known for their environmental stability? It
seems to me that the recommendation to house a suspect animal in the
"bed of a pickup truck" could engender aerosol infection of the wild
prarie dogs that often have colonies near roadways (at least here in the
West). Where is the greater risk -- possible contamination of the
environment by an infected animal shedding virus from the bed of a
truck, or extended exposure of the already-exposed human driving the
animal to the clinic?? A quick check of Field's and the CDC smallpox
vaccination recommendations did not yield any information on the
stability of orthopoxviruses in sunlight...
Maybe the recommendation should be to keep the animal in the vehicle, but
cover it with a thick blanket or towel to decrease air flow (and then
thoroughly clean the car).
--
Dave White D.V.M., Ph.D
<DMWhite@uwyo.edu>
******
[2]
Date: Thu 12 Jun 2003
From: "Javier Nevarez" <JNevarez@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>

I am writing with respect to the ProMED-mail post about recommendations for
dealing with animals potentially infected with monkeypox. The following
statement is made :
"During transport animals should be confined in a closed container such as a
cardboard box. If available, the animal should be confined in a separate
compartment of the vehicle, such as the bed of a pickup truck."
Prairie dogs and other rodents are very capable of chewing through a
cardboard box, and if that box was in the bed of a pickup truck then you
would have a potentially infected animal on the run. Perhaps a sturdier
transport container such as a small dog carrier should be suggested.
--
Javier G. Nevarez DVM
LSU School of Veterinary Medicine
Veterinary Clinical Science
Skip Bertman Dr.
Baton Rouge, LA 70803
<JNevarez@mail.vetmed.lsu.edu>
